article.description: Pau Gasol made a short spinning jumper as time expired to give the Memphis Grizzlies an 81-79 victory over the Golden State Warriors on Monday night.
article.headline: Gasol's buzzer-beater, double-double lift Grizzlies
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Pau Gasol has been making big plays all season long for the Memphis Grizzlies. Gasol made a short, spinning jumper as time expired to give the Grizzlies an 81-79 victory over the Golden State Warriors on Monday night. "I took it hard to the rim," he said. "I knew I had enough time to make a move or even change directions if I had to. I made a tough shot and we got a great win here." He recorded his second straight double-double with 23 points and 13 rebounds as the Grizzlies won consecutive games on the road for the first time since Dec. 30-31. He also led the team with six assists. "He's an All-Star, and All-Stars make big plays," Warriors guard Jason Richardson said. "We played some good defense." Derek Fisher made a driving layup with just over 3 seconds left to tie it. "That was the play we wanted to run," Gasol said. "It's worked out well in the past and it worked out perfectly again." Fisher scored 17 of his 21 points in the second half for the Warriors, who dropped to 5-11 in their last 16 home games. Mike Dunleavy added 15 points and Richardson had 10 points and 10 rebounds. The Grizzlies used their inside muscle to create second chances in the frantic final minute. With the game tied at 77 and Memphis in possession, first Gasol, then Bobby Jackson and then Eddie Jones each came up with an offensive rebound to extend the clock for the Grizzlies, who finally went ahead on a pair of free throws from Chucky Atkins with 7.5 seconds left, setting up Fisher's basket. "Pau deserves credit for making the shot at the end but the team also deserves credit," Grizzlies coach Mike Fratello said. "When we were nine down that's when we had to get some stops and work our way back in. That was just a great win." Memphis tied the game early in the fourth quarter. Dunleavy hit a 3-pointer with 8:47 remaining to give the Warriors a 70-67 lead. Golden State stayed ahead until Jones hit a 3-pointer nearly seven minutes later to put Memphis up 74-73. "Pau has been doing it for us all season and he did it again," Jones said. "He saved us." The absence of back-up center Andris Biedrins, who missed the game after getting into a minor auto accident on his way to the Arena, meant the Warriors had little room for error against Gasol. "Without Andris that complicated things," Warriors coach Mike Montgomery said. "It put us in a substitution pattern that wore us down a little. We had some strange combinations out there. Gasol made a tough shot. He jumps over the top of us and hits it." Montgomery also credited Memphis assistant coach Eric Musselman, whom he replaced as Warriors coach, for directing a defensive game plan to stop Mickael Pietrus and Richardson, who were a combined 6-of-25 from the field. "Memphis is a very good defensive team and you have to remember Eric coached theses guys," Montgomery said. "He took J.R. and Pietrus out of the game pretty well. He has the knowledge of what guys wanted to do specifically." Fisher and Richardson led Golden State's second-half surge, combining for 15 points in the third quarter. The Warriors also held Memphis to 11 points in the period, taking a 65-58 lead into the fourth. "It's been frustrating but I can't remember too many games where we just laid it down," Fisher said. "We can still get this thing done and have a good season." The officials huddled at the scorers' table twice with 7 seconds left in the first half, causing a nearly 10-minute delay. The first discussion awarded Dunleavy a pair of free throws from an incorrectly assessed foul from earlier in the quarter, while the second returned Jackson to the bench as a result of an illegal substitution. Lorenzen Wright's loose ball foul with 5:41 remaining in the half was originally recorded as an offensive foul on Jackson. Dunleavy's free throws drew the Warriors within 47-40 of Memphis at halftime.

Game notes
Grizzlies F Brian Cardinal was out with the flu and G Mike Miller missed his third straight with sprained left ankle. ... Warriors G Baron Davis (right ankle sprain) and F Troy Murphy (left ankle) were also out. ... The Warriors used their 10th different starting lineup. ... The Grizzlies' 11 third-quarter points matched their season low and also matched a season low for Warrior opponents. ... Gasol attempted a career-high 26 shots.
